1
00:00:29,000 --> 00:00:33,000
I came to Australia to study the deadliest animal in the world.

2
00:00:33,100 --> 00:00:37,000
Now, there may be some Australian audience members thinking, Struth,

3
00:00:37,100 --> 00:00:41,000
science has finally recognized the importance of the drop bears.

4
00:00:41,100 --> 00:00:45,000
But I'm not studying drop bears because around the world, by

5
00:00:45,100 --> 00:00:49,000
transmitting diseases like malaria and dengue fever, mosquitoes kill

6
00:00:49,100 --> 00:00:53,000
more than a million people every year, making them the deadliest animal on the planet.

7
00:00:53,100 --> 00:00:56,000
Now, in Australia, the most common mosquito borne disease is

8
00:00:56,100 --> 00:00:59,000
Ross River virus and it occurs at high rates in some areas,

9
00:00:59,100 --> 00:01:02,500
but not others. My question is why? What is it about certain

10
00:01:02,510 --> 00:01:05,800
areas that makes them breed disease? If we can understand the

11
00:01:05,810 --> 00:01:09,000
environmental factors that contribute to disease transmission, then we can alter

12
00:01:09,100 --> 00:01:13,000
the environment or target our control efforts to prevent human infections.

13
00:01:13,100 --> 00:01:16,000
But to answer that question, I had to find out where the

14
00:01:16,100 --> 00:01:19,800
infected mosquitoes were in South Australia. And traditionally, testing mosquitoes

15
00:01:19,810 --> 00:01:23,000
for virus has always been difficult. So I used a new technique.

16
00:01:23,100 --> 00:01:27,000
It takes these cards, which are embedded with virus preserving chemicals,

17
00:01:27,100 --> 00:01:30,750
and coats them in honey. Mosquitoes will come to feed on the

18
00:01:30,800 --> 00:01:33,600
honey and in the process, spit virus onto the card where

19
00:01:33,605 --> 00:01:36,000
it can later be detected. Now, no one had ever used

20
00:01:36,100 --> 00:01:39,000
this technique in a broad scale virus survey before, so I had

21
00:01:39,100 --> 00:01:42,000
to adapt it. I developed new traps and set them at over

22
00:01:42,100 --> 00:01:46,000
a hundred field sites across South Australia. And I captured over 20,000

23
00:01:46,100 --> 00:01:49,000
hungry mosquitoes and let them feed on the card for a week

24
00:01:49,100 --> 00:01:53,000
before testing the cards for virus. Now you may not think that

25
00:01:53,100 --> 00:01:56,000
these traps look very impressive, but science doesn't have to be beautiful.

26
00:01:56,100 --> 00:01:59,000
It has to be effective. And these traps are proving to be

27
00:01:59,100 --> 00:02:03,000
our most sensitive method of detecting infected mosquitoes. I found three types

28
00:02:03,100 --> 00:02:07,000
of infection: Ross River virus, Barmah forest virus and Stratford virus

29
00:02:07,100 --> 00:02:10,000
which has never before been found in South Australia. I now have

30
00:02:10,100 --> 00:02:13,700
the virus data I need to conduct my analysis and I'm collecting

31
00:02:13,705 --> 00:02:18,000
publicly available data about the environment surrounding my traps, like the

32
00:02:18,100 --> 00:02:21,700
density of human housing, the biodiversity of mammals and the ratio

33
00:02:21,705 --> 00:02:25,000
of green space to buildings, to see if any of those environmental

34
00:02:25,100 --> 00:02:28,800
factors can link these virus hotspots that I've shown here.

35
00:02:28,900 --> 00:02:32,000
But the most exciting part of my research so far has been the

36
00:02:32,100 --> 00:02:36,000
success of this method. Public health officials in Victoria, Queensland and

37
00:02:36,100 --> 00:02:39,000
Western Australia have been in contact with us about implementing this technique

38
00:02:39,100 --> 00:02:43,300
for their surveillance next year. And I developed these traps on a tight budget.

39
00:02:43,310 --> 00:02:46,000
I used recycled milk cartons, pantyhose and paper clips

40
00:02:46,100 --> 00:02:49,000
to make the traps. Each trap costs less than a dollar and

41
00:02:49,100 --> 00:02:51,700
can be reused for the whole season. That was important to me

42
00:02:51,710 --> 00:02:55,000
because the majority of mosquito borne disease risk happens in economically

43
00:02:55,100 --> 00:02:58,000
impoverished countries. In India, for example, where about a quarter of

44
00:02:58,100 --> 00:03:00,000
the population lives on a dollar a day,

45
00:03:01,100 --> 00:03:06,000
there are thirty three million cases of dengue infection every year. With my low budget virus

46
00:03:06,100 --> 00:03:09,000
surveillance and spatial analysis method, I can help any country regardless

47
00:03:09,100 --> 00:03:13,800
of resources find out where their deadliest animals occur, why they're there,

48
00:03:13,805 --> 00:03:18,000
and how we can stop them from infecting humans. Thanks.
